\end{bmatrix}
$$

### Step 3: Find the inverse of the encryption matrix modulo 26
The encryption matrix is:
$$
A = \begin{bmatrix}
2 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & 3 & 1 \\
1 & 1 & 4
\end{bmatrix}
$$

To find the inverse of A modulo 26, we need to find a matrix B such that \(AB \equiv I \pmod{26}\), where I is the identity matrix.

First, we find the determinant of A:
$$
\det(A) = 2(3 \cdot 4 - 1 \cdot 1) - 1(1 \cdot 4 - 1 \cdot 1) + 1(1 \cdot 1 - 3 \cdot 1) = 2(12 - 1) - 1(4 - 1) + 1(1 - 3) = 2 \cdot 11 - 1 \cdot 3 + 1 \cdot (-2) = 22 - 3 - 2 = 17
$$

Next, we find the modular inverse of 17 modulo 26. We need a number x such that \(17x \equiv 1 \pmod{26}\). Using the Extended Euclidean Algorithm, we find that \(17 \cdot 3 = 51 \equiv 1 \pmod{26}\), so the inverse of 17 modulo 26 is 3.

Now, we find the adjugate of A. The adjugate is the transpose of the cofactor matrix. The cofactor matrix is:
$$
\begin{bmatrix}
(3 \cdot 4 - 1 \cdot 1) & -(1 \cdot 4 - 1 \cdot 1) & (1 \cdot 1 - 3 \cdot 1) \\
-(1 \cdot 4 - 1 \cdot 1) & (2 \cdot 4 - 1 \cdot 1) & -(2 \cdot 1 - 1 \cdot 1) \\
(1 \cdot 1 - 1 \cdot 1) & -(2 \cdot 1 - 1 \cdot 1) & (2 \cdot 3 - 1 \cdot 1)
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
11 & -3 & -2 \\
-3 & 7 & -1 \\
0 & -1 & 5
\end{bmatrix}
$$

The adjugate is the transpose of this matrix:
$$
\begin{bmatrix}
11 & -3 & 0 \\
-3 & 7 & -1 \\
-2 & -1 & 5
\end{bmatrix}
$$

Now, we multiply the adjugate by the modular inverse of the determinant (which is 3):
$$
A^{-1} = 3 \cdot \begin{bmatrix}
11 & -3 & 0 \\
-3 & 7 & -1 \\
-2 & -1 & 5
\end{bmatrix} \pmod{26}
$$

Calculating each element modulo 26:
$$
A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix}
33 \mod 26 & -9 \mod 26 & 0 \\
-9 \mod 26 & 21 \mod 26 & -3 \mod 26 \\
-6 \mod 26 & -3 \mod 26 & 15 \mod 26
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
